SIMPLE: source
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Source
<hw>Source</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>sours</ets>,
OF. <ets>sourse</ets>, <ets>surse</ets>, <ets>sorse</ets>, F.
<ets>source</ets>, fr. OF. <ets>sors</ets>, p. p. of OF.
<ets>sordre</ets>, <ets>surdre</ets>, <ets>sourdre</ets>, to spring
forth or up, F. <ets>sourdre</ets>, fr. L. <ets>surgere</ets> to lift or
raise up, to spring up. See <er>Surge</er>, and cf. <er>Souse</er> to
plunge or swoop as a bird upon its prey.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act
of rising; a rise; an ascent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Therefore right as an hawk upon a <qex>sours</qex>⟦br⟧
Up springeth into the air, right so prayers . . . ⟦br⟧
Maken their <qex>sours</qex> to Goddes ears two.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The rising from the ground, or beginning, of a
stream of water or the like; a spring; a fountain.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where as the Poo out of a welle small⟦br⟧
Taketh his firste springing and his <qex>sours</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Kings that rule⟦br⟧
Behind the hidden <qex>sources</qex> of the Nile.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That from which anything comes forth, regarded as
its cause or origin; the person from whom anything originates; first
cause.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>source</qex> of ideas every man has wholly in
himself.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>source</qex> of Newton's light, of Bacon's sense.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Origin</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sourcrout</ent>⟦br⟧
